# HITT user-facing documentation

Applies when editing **README files** under `hitt/` and **`docs/hitt/use-cases.json`**.

Audience: Helix administrators and operators with **minimal technical skills**. Write for someone who runs commands from a guide but does not read shell scripts or source code.

## Language

- Use **plain, direct English**. Short sentences. Active voice.
- Explain **what to do**, **what happens**, and **what to do next** — not how HITT implements it.
- Prefer product terms users see in Jenkins and the UI: **HELIX_ONPREM_DEPLOYMENT**, **Helix Platform**, **Deployment Engine**, **rebuild the job**, **parameter values**.
- Avoid jargon where a simpler phrase works: say “saved settings file” before “JSON values file” if both are clear; define acronyms on first use.

## Do not include (unless explicitly developer docs)

- **Function or symbol names** from `hitt.sh` (e.g. `triggerHelixOnpremPipelineBuild`, `getPipelineSectionParams`, `PIPELINE_INPUT_JSON`).
- **Implementation details**: Groovy script console, jq filters, HTTP status codes, crumb/cookie handling, internal variable names.
- **Source file paths** (`hitt/hitt.sh`, `.cursor/`, `.githooks/`) except **`hitt.conf`** when the user must create or edit it.
- **“Under the hood”** lists of automatic steps — summarize the **user-visible outcome** in one or two sentences instead.
- **Implicit prerequisites** — do not state that a command “requires kubectl”, “needs kubectl access”, “requires cluster access”, or similar. HITT already assumes a working cluster connection; only mention extra requirements that are **not** obvious (Jenkins login, Helix Platform deployed, a specific namespace configured in HITT, metrics-server for optional columns, and so on).
- **Kubernetes object names** — do not name Deployments, StatefulSets, DaemonSets, ConfigMaps, Secrets, IngressClasses, or similar unless the user **must** know that object for the documented option (e.g. a secret name they must pass to **get secret**, or a field HITT prints and they must look up in the UI). Prefer product sections (**Helix Platform**, **Helix IS**, **Deployment Engine**) and **user-visible outcomes** over how HITT detects them in the cluster.

## OK to include

- **Commands** the user must run (`bash hitt.sh -k "get lastsuccessful"`).
- **`hitt.conf`** when the user must create or edit it (not when a mode simply runs without that file).
- **Jenkins job names** and **pipeline parameter names** when the user must fill or review them in Jenkins.
- **Links** to other README mode docs or https://bit.ly/hitthelp when pointing to more help.
- **`seeAlso` URLs** in use cases (required for the help site).
- **Optional cluster features** when absence changes behaviour (e.g. metrics-server needed for usage percentages in **info cluster**) — describe the feature, not “kubectl access”.
- **Kubernetes names** only when the doc is about that specific resource (e.g. `get secret cacerts`, or explaining a label printed by HITT that the operator must match in Jenkins).

## Use case notes (`use-cases.json`)

- **Title**: “I want to …” in everyday language.
- **Notes**: 1–3 bullets — prerequisites, expected result, next step in Jenkins or HITT. No code architecture.
- **Commands**: exact quoted CLI only; no explanation of internal functions.

## Examples

```markdown
# ❌ BAD
`build` calls `triggerHelixOnpremPipelineBuild`, which runs `getPipelineFileParams` and strips keys from `PIPELINE_INPUT_JSON`.

# ✅ GOOD
When you use **build**, HITT sends your saved settings to Jenkins but leaves out file uploads (those must be added in Jenkins). All **Pipelines** checkboxes are turned off so a full deployment does not start until you review the job.
```

```markdown
# ❌ BAD
Scans namespaces with a **rsso** Deployment, **midtier-user** Deployment, and **efk-elasticsearch-data** StatefulSet.

# ✅ GOOD
Lists **Helix Platform**, **Helix IS**, **Deployment Engine**, and **Helix Logging** namespaces, with version where available.
```

```markdown
# ❌ BAD
Requires kubectl access and a valid kubeconfig.

# ✅ GOOD
Lists Helix namespaces and versions found in the cluster.
```

```markdown
# ❌ BAD
Requires `checkJenkinsIsRunning` and a valid `Jenkins-Crumb`.

# ✅ GOOD
Requires Jenkins details in **hitt.conf** and a working login to the Deployment Engine.
```

When updating existing docs, rewrite technical passages to match this style; do not add new internal references.
